The feature you are writing about is a live update validation - I've already mentioned that the best way to implement it is to split validations of every single input into separated methods, so we could only call out the one, that is needed at a given time. 

Instead of TextWatcher we could make use of OnTextChanged listener from ButterKnife lib.

For example:
1. Username clicks on register button, but his username is incorrect
2. Username input got requested focus
3. User can now correct the input
4. OnTextChanged binded to username will check everytime when user edit input, if it's correct

It could be implemented like this:

// Listener to check correctness of triggered input
@OnTextChanged(R.id.et_username)
public void onUsernameChanged() {
    // on every text changed event, we would like to check if new provided data is correct
    validateUsername();
}

// Separated method for validation
private void validateUsername() {
    // statements to check if username is valid
   // if not - show error - else - hide error
}

You told me to write these validations in a single method like it was written before just because you said you have a better alternative which you will add to the GCI tasks in future.

Would you like me to split validations into separated methods anyway?
